04602nam a22005295i 9780889207943DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19871987xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892079437 a10.51644/97808892079432doi  a(DE-B1597)667265  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX8118.5b.H23 1986eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.6/87/0711 aHamm, Peter M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContinuity and Change Among Canadian Mennonite Brethren /cPeter M. Hamm. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[1987] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figure and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tTheoretical Framework -- tSectarianism -- tReligious Continuity and Change -- tHistorical Background -- tThe Anabaptist-Mennonite Movement -- tMennonite Brethren Beginnings -- tSacralization Of Identity -- tDelineating Boundaries -- tEnhancing Cohesion -- tConsolidating Identities -- tFacilitating Socialization -- tReinforcing Integration -- tSecularization Process -- tEducation and Relativization -- tUrbanization and Fragility Hazards -- tOccupational Change and Reorientation -- tEconomic Ascendancy and Vertical Mobility -- tAssimilation and Identity Crisis -- tViability Of Sectarianism -- tConclusion: Sectarian Persistence -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than 450 years after their birth in the Anabaptist movement, 125 years after their secession from Russian Mennonitism, and 60 years after their immigration to Canada, the Mennonite Brethren exhibit specific and measurable signs of sectarian viability and religious vitality. To explain the persistence of the sect, Hamm analyses the process of sacralization within the Canadian Mennonite Brethren Church — which “safeguards identity, a system of meaning, or a definition of reality” — and the process of secularization — which “erodes boundaries, dislodges stable structures, and destroys identity.” It is an oversimplification, the author argues, to insist that the factors of continuity — ethical and cognitive norms, family solidarity, ethnicity, worship, evangelism, community and church structures, and service agencies — are solely integrative and that the factors of change — urbanization, education, occupational change, and economic affluence — are solely disruptive. Instead, a complex dialectic between the two processes is at work that prevents restrictive rigidity within the sect and excessive accommodation to the host society. According to the author, “this analysis of the Canadian Mennonite Brethren becomes a case study to test the utility of an identity theory of religion, which hinges on the integration/differentiation dialectic. It is, at the same time, a serious self-study in religious sociology, by which the author seeks to gain a better understanding of the processes of growth and decline, of continuity and change, and of the ongoing tension resulting from the religious movement’s confrontation with society.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMennoniteszCanada. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920794340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207943/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  AC